##### 1\. Introduction  {#1.-introduction}

##### 1.1 Purpose

The primary purpose of this project is to create a Circular Dichroism Spectrometer (CD Spec) to aid research and education at St. Mary’s College of Maryland. This Software Development Plan document shall provide a detailed description of the CD Spec project and all of its components.Scheduling of the project development process shall be documented covering the entire duration of the project as well as all plans for future CD Spec project documentation.

##### 1.2 Scope {#1.2-scope}

This Software Development Plan (SDP) applies to the CD Spec software development project and provides a detailed description of the overall software development process pertaining to the project. Important dates and details pertaining to the project, including development and software deployment shall be defined and documented. All development plans described within this document shall be derived from the CD Spec software requirements and specifications as requested by the client.

##### 1.3 Definitions, Acronyms, and Abbreviations {#1.3-definitions,-acronyms,-and-abbreviations}

* **CD Spec \-** Circular Dichroism Spectrometer  
* **Q\&A** \- Quality Assurance Team  
* **R\&D** \- Research and Development Team  
* **SDP \-** Software Development Plan   
* **SRS \-** Software Requirements Specification

##### 1.4 Document References {#1.4-document-references}

* **Software Requirements Specification** **(SRS)**, v1.0, 9/17/20  
* **Traceability Matrix**, v1.0, 9/22/20

##### 1.5 System Overview {#1.5-system-overview}

The Circular Dichroism Spectrometer (CD Spec) software shall be a functional database housed within a constructed web application. This software shall be utilized by both instructors and students to monitor spectral changes in structure between protein-DNA interactions. Users of this web application shall be able to create three forms of accounts. These accounts include a public user account, a student user account, and an administrator account. Each account type shall have specific abilities and/or limitations imposed. A public user may only view submitted protein-DNA data, they may not edit the data in any way or submit data themselves. A student user may view and submit protein-DNA data, they may not edit the data in any way. An administrator has full functionality, meaning that they may view, submit, and edit all data within the database. 

This CD Spec software shall perform calculations within the backend in order to monitor changes and differences between the data within the database.the data base will be an azure database and the application will be written in jengo.

##### 2\. Project Overview {#2.-project-overview}

##### 2.1 Project Purpose, Scope, and Objectives

* Create an online database  
* User is able to download the data from database  
* Admin account, Student account, and Public account creation (admins create students)  
* Admins able to upload and change data on database  
* Students able to view and download data, but not able to upload or change data  
* Public accounts will only be able to view and download publicly released data  
* Database website will be minimalist in design. Buttons will be included. Similar to a wiki page  
* Different data will have different display types

##### 2.2 Assumptions and Constraints {#2.2-assumptions-and-constraints}

* Database will be built on a specific SMCM server (Ask Lindsay for specific name)  
* Project will have a working the end of the Fall 2020 semester  
* Only members of the COSC 401 class will be working on the development  
* Database will support JSOC and text files

##### 3\. Project Organization {#3.-project-organization}

##### 3.1 Organizational Structure

This project will be developed by an 11-person team under the supervision of Alex, the Project Leader, Cameron, the Quality Assurance & Documentation leader, and Thomas, the Research & Development Leader. The teams will work together through virtual communication and collaboration as well as following the development plans to allow flexibility in planning and approval. This allows us to work remotely but also with optimized efficiency through weekly meetings. The team will have formal management and will be directed by the Project manager and Lindsay Jamieson.

##### 4.3 Project Monitoring and Control {#4.3-project-monitoring-and-control}

*\[Address each of the following subsections in a brief, **yet accurate**, manner:\]*

##### 4.3.1 Requirements Management {#4.3.1-requirements-management}

This CD Spec spectrometer software’s requirements shall be monitored utilizing the associated Traceability Matrix as well as the project SRS document. All specified requirements and functionality will be recorded and described within those documents for the duration of the software development process. If CD Spec spectrometer software requirements are altered in any way within the duration of this software development process, the changes will be recorded within the appropriate documentation.

##### 4.3.2 Quality Control  {#4.3.2-quality-control}

To control the quality of this CD Spec spectrometer software, the research and development team as well as the documentation and quality assurance team, shall utilize applications such as Docker, Google Docs, and Trello to track and monitor software development progress. Application source code shall be posted to Docker frequently and all documentation shall be written via Google Docs and will be available for team viewing at all times. Software development tasks shall be managed via the use of Trello, where all due dates and current tasks will be posted for team benefit.

##### 4.3.3 Reporting and Measurement {#4.3.3-reporting-and-measurement}

*\[Describe reports to be generated. Specify which metrics should be collected and why. OR if available, refer to the Project Measurements and Project Measurements document.\]*

Updated schedule estimates, and metrics summary reports, will be generated at the end of each iteration. As of right now the schedule is made to only include what Q\&A will accomplish throughout the whole process. R\&D will be updated on a weekly basis to accommodate the modeling and construction structure.

##### 4.3.4 Risk Management {#4.3.4-risk-management}

*\[Describe the approach that will be used to identify, analyze, prioritize, monitor and mitigate risks. If available, refer to the Risk List document.\]*

Risks will be identified in Inception Phase and throughout the lifecycle of the project. Project risk is evaluated at least once per iteration and documented by the Risk Manager. All risks will identify and rank risk likelihood and risk consequence, as well as mitigation steps.

##### 4.3.5 Configuration Management {#4.3.5-configuration-management}

*\[Describe the process by which problems and changes are submitted, reviewed, and dispositioned. Describe how project or product artifacts are to be named, marked, and numbered, including system software, plans, models, components, test software, results and data, executables, and so on. Describe retention policies, and the back-up, disaster, and recovery plans. OR if Available, Refer to the Configuration Management Plan document.\]*

The configuration management will be controlled through docker as a means of viewing both the progress of the application and the number of iterations. The project will have iteration numbers starting in the0.1 range to post release numbers ranging from 1-X. All back up files and other variations will be kept in the docker application.
